               <p>598. <persName id="def1-598-18360201" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-598-18360201" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-598-18360201" type="age" value="24"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-598-18360201" type="surname" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-598-18360201" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM THOMAS</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18360201-598-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18360201-598-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18360201-598-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>for stealing, on the <rs id="t18360201-cd-174" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360201-598-offence-1 t18360201-cd-174"></join>25th of January</rs>, 2 pence, and 6 halfpence, the monies of <persName id="t18360201-name-1261" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1261" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1261" type="surname" value="BLACKHAM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1261" type="given" value="OBADIAH"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360201-598-offence-1 t18360201-name-1261"></join>Obadiah Blackham</persName>—2nd <hi rend="smallCaps">COUNT</hi>, stating it to be the monies of <persName id="t18360201-name-1262">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1262" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>our Lord the king</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS SHEPHERD</hi> and <hi rend="smallCaps">ADOLPHUS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360201-name-1263" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1263" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1263" type="surname" value="BLACKMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1263" type="given" value="OBADIAH"></interp>OBADIAH BLACKMAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a boot-maker, and live in High-street Borough. Mine is a receiving-house for the two-penny post office—the prisoner called at my house generally once a day, to receive the letters—I have a separate till, or drawer for the postmoney—I had from time to 22nd January, my boy made a communication to me, and on the 25th, about half-past nine o'clock in the morning, I looked into the post-office till, and there was sixpence in silver, and one penny in copper in it—I then added 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in silver to it, and 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. worth of copper, making 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—my son Henry, marked all the money in my presence about ten o'clock the prisoner came in—I had got the letters ready, all but tying up—I went into the back shop for string, and tied the letters up—I came forward, and handed them to the prisoner I had left nobody but the prisoner in the shop—I was not absent more than two minutes—when I returned, the prisoner had drawn himself from the desk, where I had left him, and stood in the middle of the shop I gave him the letters, and he was leaving the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183602010217"></xptr>
               <p>shop—my son George came out upon him, and said, "Stop, you must be searched, for money taken out of the till"—the prisoner then turned round, and said, "I hope you will forgive me, I will never do it again"—my son had said nothing else—I said I shall not forgive you, for it is not the first time you have robbed the till—I sent one of my sons for a constable, and when he came the prisoner put his hand into the right-band waistcoat pocket, and pulled out 5<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in halfpence—I looked at them, and saw the mark on them, which my son had put—I gave him into custody—he begged again hard to be forgiven—before he left the shop, I went and cast up the money in the till—I found there was 5<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. missing.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you mean to say, you cannot be mistaken about his asking forgiveness? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I an certain he did.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360201-name-1264" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1264" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1264" type="surname" value="BLACKHAM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1264" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE BLACKHAM</persName>
                  </hi>. I saw the son of the last <hi rend="italic">Witness</hi>. On the morning of the 25th of January, I saw my brother Henry mark some silver, and copper which was in the post-office till; and a little before ten o'clock, I placed myself on the top of the cellar-stairs, where there is a glass-door, through which I could see what passed in the shop, and not be seen—When the prisoner cause in, he went close up to the till—my father went into the back shop—as soon as he turned his back, I observed the prisoner put his hand into it, and took some money—my father brought him the letters—he was going out, when I came forwards, and said, "You must be searched"—I has seen him put his hand to his right-hand waistcoat pocket—he said it was the first time—I said, "It is no such thing, you did it on Friday.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360201-name-1265" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1265" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1265" type="surname" value="BRADY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1265" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY BRADY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a constable. The prisoner took the 5<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. from his pocket, and gave it to Mr. Blackham, who gave it to me—here it is,</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360201-name-1266" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1266" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
